{"title_page": "Type 5 Chi-Ri medium tank", "text_new": "{{Infobox weapon | name=Type 5 ''Chi-Ri''\n| image= Chi-Ri.JPG\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=Incomplete prototype of the Type 5 ''Chi-Ri'' after capture by American forces\n|origin= [[Empire of Japan]]\n|design_date=1943\u20131944\n|number=1 (incomplete prototype){{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}}<ref name =\"Taki\"/>\n|type=[[Medium tank]]\n|is_vehicle=yes\n|length={{convert|7.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|width={{convert|3.05 |m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|height={{convert|3.05|m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|weight=37 tonnes (40.8 US short tons; 81.571 lb){{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|suspension=Bell crank\n|speed={{convert|45|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|vehicle_range= 250 kilometers{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|primary_armament=[[Type 5 75 mm tank gun]] (L/56.4)\n|secondary_armament=[[Type 1 37 mm Anti-Tank Gun|Type 1 37 mm tank gun]]<br /> or 2 X 7.7mm [[Type 97 heavy tank machine gun]]s\n|armour={{convert|25|-|75|mm}}\n|engine=Water-cooled [[Kawasaki Aerospace Company|Kawasaki]] Type 98 aircraft engine (Petrol)\n|engine_power=550 hp (14.86 hp/tonne)\n|pw_ratio=\n|crew=5\n}}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''Type 5 medium tank Chi-Ri'''|\u4e94\u5f0f\u4e2d\u6226\u8eca \u30c1\u30ea|Go-shiki chusensha Chi-ri}} (\"Imperial Year 2605 Medium Tank Model 9\") was a [[medium tank]] developed by the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] in [[World War II]]. Intended to be a heavier, more powerful version of Japan's prototype [[Type 4 Chi-To medium tank]], in performance it was designed to surpass the US [[M4 Sherman]] medium tanks being fielded by the [[Allies of World War II|Allied forces]]. A single prototype was incomplete when the war ended.\n\n==History and development==\nBased on battlefield information from the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], Department of Arm Weaponry published a report demanding a shift of tank design focus from [[Infantry tank]] to tanks specialised for anti-tank missions. The Army's requirements for the new medium tanks were an increase of weight from 20 tonnes to 35 tonnes and an armour upgrade from 50&nbsp;mm to 75&nbsp;mm. The new tank would be mounted with a new 75&nbsp;mm gun instead of the previous 57&nbsp;mm anti-tank gun. Production focus would also prioritise quality over quantity. The new medium tank was designated as Type 5 Medium Tank Chi-Ri (\u4e94\u5f0f\u4e2d\u6226\u8eca \u30c1\u30ea).<ref>[http://ftr-wot.blogspot.com/2013/05/chi-ri-imperial-japans-most-advanced.html For the Record: Chi-Ri - Imperial Japan's most advanced tank]</ref>\n\nA single unarmed prototype of the Type 5 Chi-Ri was completed by May 1945.{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}}<ref name =\"Taki\"/> The project was abruptly abandoned to free up manpower and critical resources to concentrate on the development and production of the more practical [[Type 4 Chi-To medium tank]].{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}} As with many innovative weapons projects launched by Japan in the final years of World War II, production could not advance beyond either small numbers or the prototype stage due to material shortages, and the loss of Japan's industrial infrastructure to the [[Strategic bombing during World War II|Allied bombing of Japan]].{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|pp=3, 5, 29}} It was the last tank \"developed\" by the Imperial Japanese Army.<ref name =\"Taki\">[http://www3.plala.or.jp/takihome/chi-ri.htm Taki\u2019s Imperial Japanese Army: Type 5 Medium Tank \"Chi-Ri\"]</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Chi-Ri rear-side angle view.jpg|thumb|left|Side-rear angle view of Type 5 Chi-Ri captured, post-surrender]] \nThe Type 5 Chi-Ri featured a lengthened version of the Type 4 Chi-To chassis, with eight road wheels per side instead of the seven of the Chi-To. It had the usual Japanese track arrangement with forward mounted drive sprockets and rear mounted idlers. The Type 5 Chi-Ri had sloped welded armor, with a maximum thickness of 75&nbsp;mm at the front hull; 25\u201350&nbsp;mm on the side; 50&nbsp;mm on the rear and 50&nbsp;mm on the turret.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}<ref name=\"h\">[http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/weapons_type_5_chi_ri.html History of War: Type 5 Chi-Ri Medium Tank]</ref>\n\nThe Type 5 Chi-Ri was initially to be powered by a Mitsubishi [[Diesel engine]], but the advancements needed to provide the necessary horsepower fell behind schedule, and an 800&nbsp;hp V-12 gasoline-fueled aircraft engine designed by [[BMW]] in Germany and licensed to [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries]] in Japan was selected instead. The \"Kawasaki Type 98 800 HP engine Ha-9-IIb\" was detuned for the tank to 550&nbsp;hp.<ref name=\"h\"/>{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|pp=29, 30}}\n\n[[File:Type5 75mm tank gun 01.jpg|thumb|Type 5 75 mm tank gun Mark I (semi-auto loader)]]\nThe tank had a hexagonal [[gun turret]] and on the left side of the turret roof was a commander's cupola. In front of that was a crew hatch.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=46}} Originally, the prototype tank was to be fitted with the same [[Type 5 75 mm tank gun]] (based on the [[Type 4 75 mm AA Gun]]) used on the Type 4 Chi-To.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|pp=29, 30}} A secondary weapon of a fixed front hull-mounted Type 1 37&nbsp;mm tank gun was fitted in the position normally taken by a [[machine gun]].{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}} Alternatively, the design called for using two [[Type 97 heavy tank machine gun]]s in place of the front hull-mounted Type 1 37&nbsp;mm tank gun.<ref name =\"Taki\"/>{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}} Accordingly to another source, the design called for a ball mount for a Type 97 machine gun on the left side of the turret for use in close combat situations.<ref name=\"h\"/> There were also plans for a '''Type 5 Chi-Ri II''', to be diesel powered and using the Type 5 75&nbsp;mm tank gun as its main armament.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=29}}\n\n==Service history==\nAs with the Type 4 Chi-To tanks, the Type 5 Chi-Ri was originally considered for the final defense of the [[Japanese home islands]] against the expected [[Operation Downfall|Allied invasions]]. However, only the one unarmed prototype had been completed by the time the [[surrender of Japan|war in the Pacific came to an end]].{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=23}}\n\nThe prototype Type 5 Chi-Ri was seized by [[United States Army|American forces]] during the [[occupation of Japan]] and earmarked for tests at the [[United States Army Ordnance Museum|Aberdeen Proving Grounds]].{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=23}} According to one source, the prototype was eventually scrapped.<ref>[https://ritastatusreport.live/2017/08/08/the-final-fate-of-the-chi-ri/ Status Report: The final fate of the Chi-Ri]</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n*'''''Ho-Ri''' tank destroyer''\n[[File:IJA Experimental 105mm tank gun 01.jpg|thumb|upright|Experimental 105 mm tank gun]]\n[[File:Experimental Type 5 gun tank Ho-Ri mock-up scale model 01.jpg|thumb|220px|Experimental Type 5 gun tank Ho-Ri I mock-up scale model]]\nThe '''Ho-Ri I''' was a more powerful tank destroyer (gun tank) using a 105&nbsp;mm cannon in place of the 75&nbsp;mm gun design and an additional 37&nbsp;mm gun in the front armored plate. The armor was to be 30&nbsp;mm thick and it was to have a crew of six. It used the Type 5 Chi-Ri tank chassis. The superstructure for the main gun was placed at the rear, the engine was positioned in the center area of the chassis and the driver's station was in the front hull section; all similar in design to the German Ferdinand/[[Elefant]] heavy [[tank destroyer]].{{sfn|Tomczyk|2007|pp=10, 30}} According to \"The National Institute for Defense Studies, Ministry of Defense, Military Administration of Munitions Mobilization, Production Chart of January to April of 1945\", the plan was to produce a total of 5 Ho-Ri gun tanks by March 1945.<ref>[https://static.warthunder.ru/upload/image/2017/September/2_aa277b5ecca168516029a1b879b67680.png \"The National Institute for Defense Studies, Ministry of Defense, Military Administration of Munitions Mobilization, Production Chart of January to April of 1945\"]</ref> However, no prototypes are known to have been completed.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2007|p=10}}{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=20}}<ref>[http://www3.plala.or.jp/takihome/ho-ri.htm Taki\u2019s Imperial Japanese Army:105mm SP Gun Tank \"Ho-Ri\"]</ref><ref>Hara & Eimori. (1978) [1961]. ''Japanese Tanks & Armoured Vehicles Vol. 2.'' Tokyo: Shuppan Kyodo Sha, p. 165.</ref>  Another variant of the Ho-Ri was to have a twin 25&nbsp;mm anti-aircraft gun on top of the rear casemate superstructure in a \"swivel mount\".{{sfn|Tomczyk|2007|p=32}}\n\nA second version planned was the '''Ho-Ri II''' heavy tank destroyer. It was to use the Type 5 Chi-Ri tank chassis. The boxy superstructure for the main gun was completely integral with the hull's sides and placed at the center of the chassis (similar in design to the German [[Panzerj\u00e4ger Tiger(P) known as Elefant]]). The engine compartment was moved in the rear area of the chassis. It also was to use a 105&nbsp;mm cannon as its main armament.{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=20}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2007|pp=10, 33\u201335}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book | last = Tomczyk | first = Andrzej | year = 2005 | title = Japanese Armor Vol. 4 | publisher = AJ Press | location = | isbn = 978-8372371676 | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Tomczyk | first = Andrzej | year = 2007 | title = Japanese Armor Vol. 5 | publisher = AJ Press | location = | isbn = 978-8372371799 | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Zaloga | first = Steven J. | authorlink = Steven Zaloga | year = 2007 | title = Japanese Tanks 1939\u201345 | publisher = Osprey | location = | isbn = 978-1-8460-3091-8 | ref = harv }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | last = Hara | first = Tomio | year = 1972 | title = Japanese Medium Tanks | series = AFV Weapons Profiles No. 49 | publisher = Profile Publications Limited | ref = harv }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/weapons_type_5_chi_ri.html History of War.org]\n*[http://www3.plala.or.jp/takihome/ Taki's Imperial Japanese Army Page - Akira Takizawa]\n*[https://ritastatusreport.live/2017/08/08/the-final-fate-of-the-chi-ri/ Rita's Status Report: The final fate of the Chi-Ri]\n\n{{WWIIJapaneseAFVs}}\n{{Portal bar|Tanks}}\n\n[[Category:World War II tanks of Japan|5 Chi-Ri]]\n[[Category:Medium tanks of Japan|Type 5 Chi-Ri]]\n[[Category:History of the tank]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox weapon | name=Type 5 ''Chi-Ri''\n| image= Chi-Ri.JPG\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=Incomplete prototype of the Type 5 ''Chi-Ri'' after capture by American forces\n|origin= [[Empire of Japan]]\n|design_date=1943\u20131944\n|number=1 (incomplete prototype){{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}}<ref name =\"Taki\"/>\n|type=[[Medium tank]]\n|is_vehicle=yes\n|length={{convert|7.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|width={{convert|3.05 |m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|height={{convert|3.05|m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|weight=37 tonnes (40.8 US short tons; 81.571 lb){{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|suspension=Bell crank\n|speed={{convert|45|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|vehicle_range= 250 kilometers{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}\n|primary_armament=[[Type 5 75 mm tank gun]] (L/56.4)\n|secondary_armament=[[Type 1 37 mm Anti-Tank Gun|Type 1 37 mm tank gun]]<br /> or 2 X 7.7mm [[Type 97 heavy tank machine gun]]s\n|armour={{convert|25|-|75|mm}}\n|engine=Water-cooled [[Kawasaki Aerospace Company|Kawasaki]] Type 98 aircraft engine (Petrol)\n|engine_power=550 hp (14.86 hp/tonne)\n|pw_ratio=\n|crew=5\n}}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''Type 5 medium tank Chi-Ri'''|\u4e94\u5f0f\u4e2d\u6226\u8eca \u30c1\u30ea|Go-shiki chusensha Chi-ri}} (\"Imperial Year 2605 Medium Tank Model 9\") was a [[medium tank]] developed by the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] in [[World War II]]. Intended to be a heavier, more powerful version of Japan's prototype [[Type 4 Chi-To medium tank]], in performance it was designed to surpass the US [[M4 Sherman]] medium tanks being fielded by the [[Allies of World War II|Allied forces]]. A single prototype was incomplete when the war ended.\n\n==History and development==\nBased on battlefield information from the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], Department of Arm Weaponry published a report demanding a shift of tank design focus from [[Infantry tank]] to tanks specialised for anti-tank missions. The Army's requirements for the new medium tanks were an increase of weight from 20 tonnes to 35 tonnes and an armour upgrade from 50&nbsp;mm to 75&nbsp;mm. The new tank would be mounted with a new 75&nbsp;mm gun instead of the previous 57&nbsp;mm anti-tank gun. Production focus would also prioritise quality over quantity. The new medium tank was designated as Type 5 Medium Tank Chi-Ri (\u4e94\u5f0f\u4e2d\u6226\u8eca \u30c1\u30ea).<ref>[http://ftr-wot.blogspot.com/2013/05/chi-ri-imperial-japans-most-advanced.html For the Record: Chi-Ri - Imperial Japan's most advanced tank]</ref>\n\nA single unarmed prototype of the Type 5 Chi-Ri was completed by May 1945.{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}}<ref name =\"Taki\"/> The project was abruptly abandoned to free up manpower and critical resources to concentrate on the development and production of the more practical [[Type 4 Chi-To medium tank]].{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}} As with many innovative weapons projects launched by Japan in the final years of World War II, production could not advance beyond either small numbers or the prototype stage due to material shortages, and the loss of Japan's industrial infrastructure to the [[Strategic bombing during World War II|Allied bombing of Japan]].{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|pp=3, 5, 29}} It was the last tank \"developed\" by the Imperial Japanese Army.<ref name =\"Taki\">[http://www3.plala.or.jp/takihome/chi-ri.htm Taki\u2019s Imperial Japanese Army: Type 5 Medium Tank \"Chi-Ri\"]</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Chi-Ri rear-side angle view.jpg|thumb|left|Side-rear angle view of Type 5 Chi-Ri captured, post-surrender]] \nThe Type 5 Chi-Ri featured a lengthened version of the Type 4 Chi-To chassis, with eight road wheels per side instead of the seven of the Chi-To. It had the usual Japanese track arrangement with forward mounted drive sprockets and rear mounted idlers. The Type 5 Chi-Ri had sloped welded armor, with a maximum thickness of 75&nbsp;mm at the front hull; 25\u201350&nbsp;mm on the side; 50&nbsp;mm on the rear and 50&nbsp;mm on the turret.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}<ref name=\"h\">[http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/weapons_type_5_chi_ri.html History of War: Type 5 Chi-Ri Medium Tank]</ref>\n\nThe Type 5 Chi-Ri was initially to be powered by a Mitsubishi [[Diesel engine]], but the advancements needed to provide the necessary horsepower fell behind schedule, and an 800&nbsp;hp V-12 gasoline-fueled aircraft engine designed by [[BMW]] in Germany and licensed to [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries]] in Japan was selected instead. The \"Kawasaki Type 98 800 HP engine Ha-9-IIb\" was detuned for the tank to 550&nbsp;hp.<ref name=\"h\"/>{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|pp=29, 30}}\n\n[[File:Type5 75mm tank gun 01.jpg|thumb|Type 5 75 mm tank gun Mark I (semi-auto loader)]]\nThe tank had a hexagonal [[gun turret]] and on the left side of the turret roof was a commander's cupola. In front of that was a crew hatch.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=46}} Originally, the prototype tank was to be fitted with the same [[Type 5 75 mm tank gun]] (based on the [[Type 4 75 mm AA Gun]]) used on the Type 4 Chi-To.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|pp=29, 30}} A secondary weapon of a fixed front hull-mounted Type 1 37&nbsp;mm tank gun was fitted in the position normally taken by a [[machine gun]].{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}}{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}} Alternatively, the design called for using two [[Type 97 heavy tank machine gun]]s in place of the front hull-mounted Type 1 37&nbsp;mm tank gun.<ref name =\"Taki\"/>{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=30}} Accordingly to another source, the design called for a ball mount for a Type 97 machine gun on the left side of the turret for use in close combat situations.<ref name=\"h\"/> There were also plans for a '''Type 5 Chi-Ri II''', to be diesel powered and using the Type 5 75&nbsp;mm tank gun as its main armament.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=29}}\n\n==Service history==\nAs with the Type 4 Chi-To tanks, the Type 5 Chi-Ri was originally considered for the final defense of the [[Japanese home islands]] against the expected [[Operation Downfall|Allied invasions]]. However, only the one unarmed prototype had been completed by the time the [[surrender of Japan|war in the Pacific came to an end]].{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=22}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=23}}\n\nThe prototype Type 5 Chi-Ri was seized by [[United States Army|American forces]] during the [[occupation of Japan]] and earmarked for tests at the [[United States Army Ordnance Museum|Aberdeen Proving Grounds]].{{sfn|Tomczyk|2005|p=23}} According to one source, the prototype was eventually scrapped.<ref>[https://ritastatusreport.live/2017/08/08/the-final-fate-of-the-chi-ri/ Status Report: The final fate of the Chi-Ri]</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n*'''''Ho-Ri''' tank destroyer''\n[[File:IJA Experimental 105mm tank gun 01.jpg|thumb|upright|Experimental 105 mm tank gun]]\n[[File:Experimental Type 5 gun tank Ho-Ri mock-up scale model 01.jpg|thumb|220px|Experimental Type 5 gun tank Ho-Ri I mock-up scale model]]\nThe '''Ho-Ri I''' was a more powerful tank destroyer (gun tank) using a 105&nbsp;mm cannon in place of the 75&nbsp;mm gun design and an additional 37&nbsp;mm gun in the front armored plate. The armor was to be 30&nbsp;mm thick and it was to have a crew of six. It used the Type 5 Chi-Ri tank chassis. The superstructure for the main gun was placed at the rear, the engine was positioned in the center area of the chassis and the driver's station was in the front hull section; all similar in design to the German Ferdinand/[[Elefant]] heavy [[tank destroyer]].{{sfn|Tomczyk|2007|pp=10, 30}} According to \"The National Institute for Defense Studies, Ministry of Defense, Military Administration of Munitions Mobilization, Production Chart of January to April of 1945\", the plan was to produce a total of 5 Ho-Ri gun tanks by March 1945.<ref>[https://static.warthunder.ru/upload/image/2017/September/2_aa277b5ecca168516029a1b879b67680.png \"The National Institute for Defense Studies, Ministry of Defense, Military Administration of Munitions Mobilization, Production Chart of January to April of 1945\"]</ref> However, no prototypes are known to have been completed.{{sfn|Tomczyk|2007|p=10}}{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=20}}<ref>[http://www3.plala.or.jp/takihome/ho-ri.htm Taki\u2019s Imperial Japanese Army:105mm SP Gun Tank \"Ho-Ri\"]</ref><ref>Hara & Eimori. (1978) [1961]. ''Japanese Tanks & Armoured Vehicles Vol. 2.'' Tokyo: Shuppan Kyodo Sha, p. 165.</ref>  Another variant of the Ho-Ri was to have a twin 25&nbsp;mm anti-aircraft gun on top of the rear casemate superstructure in a \"swivel mount\".{{sfn|Tomczyk|2007|p=32}}\n\nA second version planned was the '''Ho-Ri II''' heavy tank destroyer. It was to use the Type 5 Chi-Ri tank chassis. The boxy superstructure for the main gun was completely integral with the hull's sides and placed at the center of the chassis (similar in design to the German [[Jagdtiger]]). The engine compartment was moved in the rear area of the chassis. It also was to use a 105&nbsp;mm cannon as its main armament.{{sfn|Zaloga|2007|p=20}}{{sfn|Tomczyk|2007|pp=10, 33\u201335}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book | last = Tomczyk | first = Andrzej | year = 2005 | title = Japanese Armor Vol. 4 | publisher = AJ Press | location = | isbn = 978-8372371676 | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Tomczyk | first = Andrzej | year = 2007 | title = Japanese Armor Vol. 5 | publisher = AJ Press | location = | isbn = 978-8372371799 | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Zaloga | first = Steven J. | authorlink = Steven Zaloga | year = 2007 | title = Japanese Tanks 1939